 over time, which means value will need to accrue to token holders.=C2=A0
The rest of this piece is about figuring out whether web3 makes those two s=
eemingly contradictory ideas =E2=80=93 extracting less and capturing more v=
alue =E2=80=93 possible. (Hint: I think it can.)
That requires understanding how marketplaces have typically worked.
Web2 Marketplaces and the Take Rate Temptation
First things first: I think Web2 marketplaces are great. I ordered dinner o=
n DoorDash last night. I took an Uber home the night before that. I=E2=80=
=99m staying in an Airbnb later this week.=C2=A0
Marketplaces are some of the biggest and most impressive businesses built i=
n the past two decades. Even after recent selloffs, they=E2=80=99re worth h=
undreds of billions of combined dollars, all value created in the past deca=
de or so (except eBay, which I think came out of Bell Labs in the1950s):=C2=
=A0
These marketplaces not only organized existing markets and stole share from=
 incumbents; they grew the markets in which they operate through their exis=
tence. The vacation rental market is bigger because Airbnb exists. Rideshar=
ing is bigger because Uber exists. Done right, marketplaces attract and mat=
ch new supply and new demand while removing friction and lowering costs. Gr=
eat stuff. Love Web2 marketplaces.=C2=A0
But there are also challenges with the model, or opportunities for improvem=
ent:=C2=A0
Like the fact that marketplaces need to pay a lot to acquire both supply an=
d demand, often over and over. See: the bloody Uber v Lyft battle.=C2=A0
Or that so many successful marketplace businesses end up becoming advertisi=
ng businesses =E2=80=93 great for the business, annoying for the customer. =
See: all of the national fast food chain advertisements at the top of your =
DoorDash screen.=C2=A0
Or that at some point, in order to increase supply, they drop the quality b=
ar and people figure out how to game the system and it gets really hard to =
figure out what=E2=80=99s good and what=E2=80=99s not. See: Amazon third-pa=
rty sellers.
Or that successful marketplaces often increase take rates in order to incre=
ase profits once they believe participants are sufficiently locked in that =
they won=E2=80=99t leave. See: practically every marketplace in the history=
 of marketplaces.=C2=A0
To learn more about why web2 marketplaces switch from attract to extract an=
d why they often do it too early, how Braintrust works and why it can keep =
take rates lower, longer, how value accrues to the token, and the answer to=
 the question =E2=80=94 how can a user-owned network both create and captur=
e more value=E2=80=A6.=20
